gesloten om aen hem dat gelt te behandighen van
mijns tweghen: ick en hebbe geen ander occasie
om costij gelt te hebben soo denckehet selve aen ul
niet en sal in comoderen, maer disponeert van de
selve weirde sal hier, want voor 10 april en sal costij
geen gelt hebben: gelieft hier in ul de voorte doen
om de moier op de goede maniere te behandighen
hij oont bij, oft ontrent lijns, gelove ul kemwy
korne op dat het niet verkert bestert wordt
waermede
don antonio Huldalgo Antw 16fe6 1682
gent
mons wij sijn seer verobigert aen ul voorden goeder
dinste aen ons gedaen, in di reckerie van de voleurs
van onsen kanten, icl wenste wel dat ul groeten
debvoeren hadden geloont geweest, met het succes
tgene wij wel hebben verwacht, des niet tegenstande
versehere ul als mede uyt den naem van de
voordere geinterressorde, dat wij ul groote genegentijt
& sufilitijt altijt sulle arkennen: terwijlen my
noch wijders suplieeren seer mindelyck dat ul
gelilft dinst te doen, ons tot den uytersten daer
in bij te staen, ende te assisteren, op dat wij mogen
daer over meerdere satis facsie bekomen, want
met dese bedrofden tijt een groet voylis is, ende
het rijsde deel niet ten vollen in werden is
gerecjprieert daer af dan noch omte onkosten
moeten: daer en tusschen brenger deser 8 frangs
herrebout sal ul vijstigh pate comstellen de welcke
hopa ul sal gelieven te aenverden, tot teecken
van t gene wij ons capabel ordelen tot recompenie
van ul. menigh ouldighe moyten te konnen
presenteren: niet teyen stande soo mij de ulste
oft noch pertije mochten wederom bekomen van de
depolierde hanten, wij sullen geirne het voorss
verdibleren in alle ocasie tonen de obligatie
de wij hebben te sijn mech ul bel gelijft elen
soriipul te nemer over ouse prefaitatie door
kan de van fransuls arbout al soo hij nist
en welt waer om sulxx geschiet
Londen m. Abram Vivian
mij last to you was on the 14 cur. to which referre you, sence have ricd of 13d., here you
have yo acctt cur, which please to examin, & finding all right note accordingley, by
that is due to you £1259„ 13.6, witheut my preiudice, & yett there is for yd acctt. irstanding
out debts vere neare £2000 - so you may iudge what in am in disbuise & upon my acctt
cur. I make you debbor £12„6:1 st whes you drew so much upon mee you promised
deprovide for the payment, & noth with standing my continuall writing & desiring afritance
you have not been pleased to answer, butt wen you thought the bills were discharged, you
for bid mee to draw, on you dincetely as beeng agemust yd & my Intrest how would
you thinck then that I should draw on you dixeetely, though I have been foreed to do
so in the last bill of £120- to mr. Paris slaughtes: I past my bill on mr. Cole, as
being yd. intimate, & yett you had not discorsed him about itt, sure you ought so have
persuaded him to give honour to my bill, though I know, he would do to for my sake
for the future I hope you will avorde those thinghs, for I do not love them att all you
have provided about 79 bayes and as many more ander hand pray do all you can
to gett them dispatched, for they are wanting here, so sI'll depend upon them o
firtt vessel, feule not te send mee my acct you seem to reselve to sarve for post
hitt you say not wheater, I could wish to see you here
C 15d
London pr. Jean Cole
I have before mee yd. of 20„ 30 & 31 past, in the first yd bill for acc of m. Lobb, is duely
accepted, & will be payd accordingly, with thanckes for yd civilitie, besides that I am obliged
for yd kinduse to acept my bill of £72- either for my or m. Abram Vivians acctt., I
hope he hadh given you contew. before now, or att lahst promised to movide the needfull before
due, I confets I have much of is in my handes, & do much avoid redraning, butt this
& could not do, for this time a yeare is mony oxtreomly scarfy, & I thinck not au intiest
to draw on fuin dixcetely, so I hoye you will not take itt ill in my or his behalfe. as for
the £11:14.2 you mention I'll examine itt & finding itt to be right shall make good
that ballance as also of the estan of J.S. his accctt butt as yett I have not reed
one farthing this yeare of itt, wee are here in avere poore condition the last mimdations
have don us a would of dammidge, yett I hope to help yd as well as my self vee
speedly ndd of that concernes of JV, for I love vere much even acctt. & princigally
what hath hanged so long in other handes, tnext shall send a proiect of a release
to be fingned, the best new cloverseed is to bee hadd att 3½ a 4 sivers a pourd
some att 3 st, old att 2 & 22 & 1¾, the charges on either att ostend aboard will
be vere inconsidecabel besides the provision, for itt bayes no duties att all, so ondly
prouision, bannells & traight to ostend is to be rekoned, which will not come altoghether
of a stiver att a the weight is better as in England, I have sended severall of
late to England of sevenall prjses, if I can serve you please to command mee
friely, & I'll serve you as well as can beexpected from any one on this side
seeds will aise more & are resen, butt as yett vere luttle
